# .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

## Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 5+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no equivalent needed
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never thrown** by the runtime

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerThread = new Thread(ProcessLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock waits
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on `Monitor.Wait`, `Socket.Read`, etc., cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** pass `CancellationToken` into blocking APIs or use async alternatives. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `token.WaitHandle`** | Replace any `Thread.Sleep(n)` inside the loop with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(n)` so cancellation is immediate. |
| **`Thread.Join` can still hang** | If the worker ignores the token, `Join(timeout)` returns `false`. Decide whether to log and abandon, or escalate — but you **cannot** force-kill it. |
| **Catch specificity** | Always use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated `OperationCanceledException`s from inner calls. |

## Async Alternative (Preferred for .NET 8)

If possible, migrate to `BackgroundService` with fully async I/O:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This integrates with the generic host (`IHost`) and gets proper DI, logging, and lifecycle management for free via `Host.CreateDefaultBuilder`.
